Last week I flew out to Alberta to do a mountaineering course in the Rockies. The goal of this course was to learn the basics of mountain climbing - specifically glacier traverse - and how to do it safely (there’s a lot that can kill you up there).

The course culminated in an attempt to summit Mount Athabasca, an 11,500 foot peak located about 2 hours north of Banff, AB.

Over the course of the next few days I’ll be documenting the process here as well as one large video on YT next week summarizing the entire trip.

▪️What did we have to learn?
▪️How hard was it?
▪️Did we reach the summit?

Stay tuned and you’ll find out ✌🏻

It has been a LONG time since I have addressed this topic, but I think with the changes in the fitness industry over the last few years, it is necessary to discuss it one more time. Especially with the rise of TikTok, I have seen an increase in young, allegedly natural bodybuilders with fantastic physiques who are attracting controversy and sometimes even accusations of fraud. This can become a problem, especially when this complicated question is oversimplified into just a "Yes or No" or "Natty or Not" statement.

Far too often I see individuals doing themselves a disservice by being overly cynical and assuming that anyone who is somewhat muscular must be "juicing". However on the flip side, I also see people (usually younger lifters) who are taken advantage of by those who attain their physiques using PED's💉, yet claim to be as pure as the driven snow having never taken anything besides creatine.

So in this video series, I will attempt to answer this question once and for all. We will be looking at multiple variables which will culminate in one final system or "formula" for answering this question. I hope you guys like it, and remember to keep an open mind.
